{{use dmy dates|date=June 2014}} {{use list-defined references|date=June 2014}} {{Use British English|date=June 2014}} {{Infobox goat breed | name = Cilentana Grigia | image = | image_size = 280px | image_alt = | image_caption = | status = {{nobreak|[[FAO]] (2007): endangered<ref name=barb/>}} | altname = | nickname = | country = Italy | distribution = [[province of Salerno]] | standard = [http://www.assonapa.it/norme_ecc/CAPRINI-RA_Standard_WEB/Cilentana%20Grigia.htm MIPAAF] | use = milk, also meat<ref name=bigi/> | maleweight = 70 kg<ref name=pulina/> | femaleweight = 50 kg<ref name=pulina/> | maleheight = 77 cm<ref name=pulina/> | femaleheight = 70 cm<ref name=pulina/> | type = | skincolor = grey to black | woolcolor = grey | facecolor = grey | horns = about 50% are horned<ref name=aspa3/> | beard = males bearded, females 80% bearded<ref name=aspa3/> | tassels = 60% with tassels<ref name=aspa3/> | note = }}
The '''Cilentana Grigia''' is an indigenous [[breed]] of [[goat|domestic goat]] from the [[province of Salerno]], in [[Campania]] in southern Italy.<ref name=dad/> It takes its name from the geographical region of the [[Cilento]], much of which is today within the [[Parco Nazionale del Cilento, Vallo di Diano e Alburni]], and is raised mainly in that area, but also in the [[Monti Alburni]] and the [[Monti Picentini]].<ref name=bigi/> It is one of three indigenous goat breeds in the Cilento, the others being the [[Cilentana Fulva]] and the [[Cilentana Nera]]. The Cilentana Grigia is found on lower ground and richer pasture than the [[Cilentana Nera]], and is raised mainly for milk. The origins of the breed are obscure; it shows the influence of the [[Maltese (goat)|Maltese]] and [[Garganica]] breeds, and similarities to other Italian grey breeds such as the [[Ciociara Grigia]] of [[Lazio]] and the [[Argentata dell'Etna]] from Sicily.<ref name=bigi/>
The Cilentana Grigia is one of the forty-three autochthonous Italian goat breeds of limited distribution for which a herdbook is kept by the [[Associazione Nazionale della Pastorizia]], the Italian national association of sheep- and goat-breeders.<ref name=dm/><ref name=aspa/> In 2008, 768 head were registered; at the end of 2013 the registered population was 134.<ref name=aspa2/>
