{{Infobox prepared food | name = Isku-dheh karis | image = | caption = | alternate_name = | country = [[Somalia]] | region = | creator = | course = [[lunch]] or [[dinner]] | type = | served = | main_ingredient = [[rice]] and [[meat]] | variations = | calories = | other = }}
'''Isku-dheh karis''' is a Somali rice dish consisting of a mix of meat pieces, rice andsome vegetables. The term literally means "cooked mixed together", therefore it is sometimes used to more broadly refer to other grain-derived crops that require similar cooking. Hence the more specific term for this dish is '''bariis isku dheh karis'''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Jacob|first1=Jeanne|title=The World Cookbook for Students|date=2006|page=xv}}</ref> It can be served with various meats including chicken, mutton, fish or camel meat. Some Somali restaurants serve it with a banana. This rice dish is often served from a clay pot called ''baris dhari'', which serves to impart flavor from food cooked in metal pots.<ref>Culture and Customs of Somalia Culture and Customs of Somalia - Page 112, Mohamed Diriye Abdullahi</ref>
