{{Infobox military structure |name = Victoria Battery |native_name = |partof = [[Fortifications of Gibraltar]] |location =[[Gibraltar]] |image = [[File:Garrison Library Picture - VictoriaBatery.jpg|240px]] |caption = by [[Thomas Colman Dibdin]] |map_type = Gibraltar |map_size = 300 |map_alt = |map_caption = Location in [[Gibraltar]] |type = [[Artillery Battery]] |coordinates = {{coord|36.132171|-5.352193|type:landmark_region:GI|display=inline}} |code = |built = 1883 |builder = |materials = |height = |used = |demolished = |condition = |ownership = [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] |open_to_public = |controlledby = |garrison = |current_commander = |commanders = |occupants = |battles = |events = |image2 = |caption2 = }} '''Victoria Battery''' (one of two identically-named batteries named after [[Queen Victoria]]) was an [[artillery battery]] in the [[British Overseas Territories|British Overseas Territory]] of [[Gibraltar]]. It was built in the 1840s on top of the earlier Princess of Wales Batteries following a report by Major-General Sir [[John Thomas Jones]] on Gibraltar's defences. The battery was located on the west side of Gibraltar and was one of a number of "retired" batteries in the territory, constructed to improve the coastal defences between [[Europa Point]] and the town.<ref name="Hughes369">{{cite book|title=Strong as the Rock of Gibraltar|last1=Hughes|first1=Quentin|last2=Migos|first2=Athanassios|publisher=Exchange Publications|year=1995|page=369}}</ref>
The battery was completed by 1843 and was nicknamed "Snake in the Grass Battery" due to its irregular undulating shape, measuring about {{convert|200|yd}} long. It mounted fifteen 32-pdr. guns in 1850, seven of which were replaced in 1863 by 68-pdrs. In 1868 Colonel W.F.D. Jervois wrote a report into the defences of Gibraltar which recommended installing larger [[rifled muzzle loader]] (RML) guns. Two 9-inch RMLs were installed in the south flank with iron casemates providing protection. This reduced the space available for the other guns to seven emplacements, of which three were occupied by 80-pdr. RMLs by 1888. The 9-inch RMLs were later replaced by 10-inch RMLs but all of the 80-pdrs. were removed in 1892, followed by the 10-inch guns in 1900.<ref name="Hughes369" />
In 1878 a new battery, also called [[Victoria Battery (100 ton gun)|Victoria Battery]], was constructed on the right flank of the earlier battery to house a [[100 ton gun]]. It was completed in 1883 but fell into disuse within only five years, by which time the gun was already obsolete.<ref name="Hughes370">{{cite book|title=Strong as the Rock of Gibraltar|last1=Hughes|first1=Quentin|last2=Migos|first2=Athanassios|publisher=Exchange Publications|year=1995|page=370}}</ref>
